# AI Writing System

## Core Principle

- Do not rely on implicit model memory.
- Store important canon, continuity, and process state in project files.

## Scope

- These rules are global and apply to all books and series in the workspace.
- Book-specific or series-specific rules may define language, genre, tone, POV, pacing, and target chapter length.
- Local book or series rules override global stylistic defaults, but must not break canon consistency inside that project.
- Every active project must behave in one of two modes:
  - `standalone`: one project equals one book.
  - `series`: one project equals a multi-book series with volume-specific subfolders.

## Structure

- Each project lives under `books/<project_id>/`.
- `standalone` projects store chapter files directly in `chapters/`.
- `series` projects store long-range canon at the project root and active-book material inside `volumes/<book_id>/`.
- Each project maintains memory files in `memory/`.
- `series` projects may additionally maintain volume-local memory inside `volumes/<book_id>/memory/`.
- Role prompts live in `system/prompts/` and are used by workflow stage.
- Agent-specific cross-book mistakes may live in `system/mistakes/` and are read through the matching stage prompt when relevant.

## Required Context

- Before planning, writing, revising, or updating memory, read the relevant local rules for the active project if they exist.
- Before each workflow stage, read the matching file in `system/prompts/` for that stage.
- Before each workflow stage, read the matching global mistakes file in `system/mistakes/` if it exists.
- Determine the active scope before any stage:
  - `standalone`: the project root is the active scope.
  - `series`: the project root is the series scope and one `volumes/<book_id>/` directory is the active volume scope.
- Before writing or revising a chapter in a `standalone` project, read:
  - `outline.md`
  - `characters.md`
  - relevant memory files
  - previous canon chapter when available
  - approved chapter plan when available
- Before writing or revising a chapter in a `series` project, read:
  - series-level `outline.md`
  - series-level `characters.md`
  - series-level `world-rules.md` and `timeline.md` when present
  - series-level relevant memory files
  - active volume `outline.md`
  - active volume `characters.md` and `timeline.md` when present
  - active volume relevant memory files
  - previous canon chapter in the active volume when available
  - approved active-volume chapter plan when available

## Global Constraints

- Do not rewrite full memory files when a targeted update is enough.
- Do not introduce major canon elements without recording them in the appropriate project files.
- Preserve character consistency, world rules, and timeline consistency.
- Treat accepted chapter files and approved revisions as canon unless the user explicitly changes canon.
- In `series` projects, keep series-level canon and volume-level canon distinct instead of collapsing them into one file by habit.
